Determination of total CO2 in melt inclusions with shrinkage bubbles

Highlights

  • •

    Melt inclusion CO2 is accurately determined by combined in-situ analytical technique.

  • •

    Large melt inclusions tend to have more angular shape shown by micro X-ray CT images.

  • •

    CO2 in glass in melt inclusions is controlled by composition-dependent solubility.

  • •

    Bubble volume percentage is controlled by cooling and water degassing.

  • •

    Lower bound of CO2 concentration in HIMU magmas is determined.

Abstract

The compositions of volatiles in magmas can be estimated using melt inclusions encapsulated in phenocrysts. Shrinkage bubbles are occasionally observed in natural and rehomogenized melt inclusions. Because of the low solubility of CO2 in melts, CO2 is partitioned in both the melts and shrinkage bubbles in melt inclusions. We developed a method to determine total CO2 in melt inclusions by measuring (1) CO2 concentration in glass with secondary-ion mass spectrometry, (2) CO2 density in bubbles with micro-Raman spectrometry, and (3) bubble/glass volume ratio with micro X-ray computed tomography on rehomogenized melt inclusions. We applied this method to olivine-hosted melt inclusions in high-μ (HIMU)-type ocean island basalts from Raivavae in Austral Islands in French Polynesia.

The shape of melt inclusions is predominantly related to their size; larger melt inclusions tend to be more angular than smaller ones. The volume of large melt inclusions may be overestimated by previous approaches in which the dimension of melt inclusions was measured by microscopy and the volume was calculated assuming ellipsoidal shape. CO2 dissolved in glass in rehomogenized melt inclusions ranges up to ~7000 ppm. The glass with a more alkalic composition shows greater CO2 concentration than that with a less alkalic composition in accordance with the composition-dependent CO2 solubility. By contrast, the correlation between the total CO2 content and the chemical composition of the glass is unclear because CO2 in shrinkage bubbles is generally greater than that in the glass. Some melt inclusions demonstrate an extremely high total CO2 content (up to 25,000 ppm). Because these melt inclusions show a large bubble volume proportion in melt inclusions (>12 vol%), they are likely formed by the simultaneous entrapment of melts and fluids during the host olivine growth. Excluding these melt inclusions, the total CO2 content and CO2/Nb ratio in melt inclusions were up to 7000 ppm and 200, respectively. This study offers an accurate determination of CO2 concentration and CO2/Nb of the HIMU basalts from Raivavae.

1. Introduction

Volatiles play an important role in magma generation and subsequent ascent toward the Earth's surface. Volatiles reduce the rock melting temperature, thereby enhancing melt production, even in a cold mantle region, such as subduction zones (Gill, 1981; Tatsumi and Eggins, 1995). In a hot upwelling mantle, volatile-rich melts generated at great depth would segregate from the residual mantle, migrate upward, and facilitate further melting at a shallow depth (Dasgupta and Hirschmann, 2006; Green, 1973). A volcanic eruption is driven by the exsolution of volatiles from magmas when they are saturated in melts (e.g., Dixon, 1997; Edmonds and Woods, 2018; Papale and Polacci, 1999). The estimation of volatile contents in primary magmas and their mantle sources has become a focus of many researchers in mantle geochemistry and volcanology (e.g., Barry et al., 2019; Cabral et al., 2014; De Vivo et al., 2005; Kendrick et al., 2014; Métrich and Wallace, 2008; Moretti et al., 2019; Neave et al., 2014; Tucker et al., 2019).

Volatiles are easily degassed from magmas in low-pressure environments, which hampers estimating volatile contents in pre-eruption magmas from subaerially erupted volcanic rocks. Instead, quenched volcanic glasses of submarine erupted lavas are often used for volatile measurements because magmatic volatiles may be confined in them under hydraulic pressure. However, such glasses are exclusively available at oceanic volcanoes, where lavas were obtained from the seafloor during submarine surveys (Davis and Clague, 2003; Dixon and Clague, 2001; Jackson et al., 2015; Kendrick et al., 2014; Le Voyer et al., 2015; Macpherson et al., 2005; Roberge et al., 2004; Saal et al., 2002; Shimizu et al., 2016; Workman et al., 2006). Moreover, volatiles with low melt solubility tend to be saturated and thus partially degassed from the magmas even under hydraulic pressure (e.g., Esposito et al., 2014; Jackson et al., 2015; Kent, 2008; Métrich and Wallace, 2008).

Melt inclusions hosted in phenocrysts are increasingly used for the study of volatiles in magmas and their mantle sources (Cabato et al., 2015; Cabral et al., 2013, Cabral et al., 2014; Hauri, 2002; Le Voyer et al., 2010; Lowenstern, 1995; Manzini et al., 2017; Métrich and Wallace, 2008; Michael et al., 2002; Moore, 2008; Mormone et al., 2011; Narvaez et al., 2018; Plank et al., 2013; Portnyagin et al., 2007; Rose-Koga et al., 2012; Rowe et al., 2009; Shaw et al., 2008; Shimizu et al., 2009; Sobolev and Chaussidon, 1996; Wallace, 2005). Melt inclusions represent a melt composition at the time of melt encapsulation in phenocrysts during crystallization. Volatile composition in melt inclusions may have been blurred by post-entrapment effects, including in-situ crystallization, diffusive loss (of H2O in particular) through host crystals, and bubble formation caused by the shrinkage of melts during cooling (Bucholz et al., 2013; Chen et al., 2011; Danyushevsky et al., 2002; Frezzotti, 2001; Gaetani et al., 2012; Kent, 2008; Moore et al., 2015; Wallace et al., 2015). However, if the post-entrapment effects are restored, then the melt inclusions should provide reliable information on volatile composition in magmas when they are encapsulated in phenocrysts.

In this paper, we discuss a method to determine volatile contents in bubble-bearing melt inclusions. Shrinkage bubbles are frequently observed in natural and experimentally rehomogenized melt inclusions. The abundance of volatiles with relatively high melt solubility, such as H2O, S, Cl, and F, is believed to be negligibly low in shrinkage bubbles (Esposito et al., 2014; Shaw et al., 2008; Wallace et al., 2015). Therefore, the total amount in melt inclusions can be approximated by the abundance in glass (former melts) measured by electron probe microanalyzer, Fourier transform infrared spectrometer (FT-IR), or secondary-ion mass spectrometer (SIMS). By contrast, CO2 may be distributed in glass and bubbles because of its low melt solubility (Brooker et al., 2001; Dixon, 1997; Moore et al., 2015; Mysen et al., 1975; Shaw et al., 2008; Steele-MacInnis et al., 2011; Wallace et al., 2015). In some cases, shrinkage bubbles accommodate more CO2 than glass (Anderson and Brown, 1993; Esposito et al., 2011; Hartley et al., 2014; Moore et al., 2015; Wallace et al., 2015). Moreover, carbon in melt inclusions may be partially trapped in precipitated carbonates that are occasionally observed in shrinkage bubbles and the inclusion-host mineral interface (Esposito et al., 2014; Helo et al., 2011; Wallace et al., 2015).

A theoretical way to estimate the total CO2 in melt inclusions is to measure CO2 content in glass with FT-IR or SIMS and to simulate the amount of CO2 in bubbles using thermodynamic equations (Anderson and Brown, 1993; Maclennan, 2017; Shaw et al., 2008; Steele-MacInnis et al., 2011). However, it has been challenging to determine melt contraction and chemical equilibrium between bubbles and melts for rapidly cooled melt inclusions. An alternative way to estimate CO2 in bubbles is to measure CO2 density in the fluid phase and volume proportion between bubbles and glass. CO2 density in the fluid phase is reliably quantified using micro-Raman spectrometry (Aster et al., 2016; Esposito et al., 2011; Hartley et al., 2014; Kawakami et al., 2003; Moore et al., 2015; Yamamoto and Kagi, 2006). In many previous studies, however, the volume proportion between bubbles and glass was calculated by measuring their horizontal dimensions using a microscope or secondary electron microprobe (SEM) (Esposito et al., 2014; Hartley et al., 2014; Tucker et al., 2019; Wallace et al., 2015). Thus, the volume of bubbles and glass in melt inclusions can be calculated by estimating their vertical dimension (i.e., perpendicular to the microscope or SEM plane), which is difficult to accurately determine, along with the shape of bubbles and glass.

Here, we applied a micro X-ray computed tomography (MXCT) technique to quantitatively determine the shape and dimensions of bubbles and glass in melt inclusions. The MXCT technique has been recently applied for analyzing the microscale structure of minerals and inclusions (e.g., Créon et al., 2018; Horton et al., 2015; Miller et al., 2019). A three-dimensional (3D) image of melt inclusions is acquired using this technique because of the density contrast among bubbles, glass, and host phenocrysts. A shape analysis with the MXCT technique is combined with the micro-Raman spectrometry and SIMS to determine CO2 distribution in bubbles and glass, respectively, in melt inclusions, and accordingly to simulate the total CO2 in melt inclusions. The effectiveness of the technique is assessed using rehomogenized melt inclusions in olivine in ocean island basalts from Raivavae in Austral Islands, South Pacific. The melt inclusions were fused and quenched in a heating stage to dissolve small crystals and possible carbonate precipitates in them prior to chemical analyses.

2. Samples and experimental methods

The host Raivavae basalts are classified into two groups by age and isotopic composition (Hanyu et al., 2019; Lassiter et al., 2003; Lassiter et al., 2002; Maury et al., 2013; Miyazaki et al., 2018). The older Rairua Formation basalts are characterized by radiogenic Pb isotopic composition, also known as high-μ (HIMU; μ = 238U/204Pb). The younger Anatonu Formation basalts have moderately radiogenic Pb isotopes. The binary isotopic composition results from the mixing of melts from the depleted mantle source and HIMU mantle source. Olivine samples that bear melt inclusions were collected from Rairua and Anatonu basalts. The forsterite contents in the host olivine range from 77 to 86 (Hanyu et al., 2019). Melt inclusions studied in this paper are partly devitrified, including glass, clinopyroxene, hornblende, FeTi oxides, spinel, and sulfides, and are generally associated with shrinkage bubbles. They were rehomogenized on a heating stage by reheating and subsequent quenching. Major and trace element compositions, Cl concentration, and Pb isotope ratios of most melt inclusions studied here were previously reported (Hanyu et al., 2019).

Olivine grains that bear melt inclusion(s) were mounted on acryl resin and then doubly polished without exposing them using a lapping film with alumina particles. Doubly polished olivine grains, including melt inclusions, had thickness between 200 and 500 μm. After removing acryl resin with acetone, the samples were ultrasonically cleaned in Milli-Q water and then dried. Each olivine was placed on a heating stage (TS1500; Linkam Scientific) and heated in an Ar atmosphere until melt inclusion(s) were molten by monitoring them under a microscope. The accuracy of the temperature on the heating stage was estimated using a gold piece, measured melting temperature of which was about 1050 °C. The melting temperature is typically between 1180 °C and 1280 °C (Supplementary Table S1). Plural bubbles in a melt inclusion were merged to become a single bubble under melting conditions. After keeping the melting temperature for 5 min, melt inclusions were quenched by taking the sample plate out from the heating furnace. Any melt inclusions that burst or cracked during heating experiments were discarded. Rehomogenized melt inclusions were glassy and light brown. Shrinkage bubbles did not disappear after rehomogenization for all samples.

The density of CO2 in shrinkage bubbles in the melt inclusions was determined using micro-Raman spectroscopy at the Hokkaido University Museum. The analytical details are given elsewhere (Hagiwara et al., 2018; Takahata et al., 2014). CO2 in bubbles was excited using an Ar laser (514.5 nm, 543-AP-A01; Melles Griot) and the Raman spectrum was monitored using a spectrometer (Acton SP-2750; Princeton Instruments, Inc.) and a CCD camera (1650 × 200 pixels, 16 μm width, iVac; Andor Technology), achieving a wavenumber resolution of 0.32 cm−1 using a grating of 1800 lines/mm. An analysis for 100 s in each set of measurements was repeated three times, and the data were averaged after removing a spike noise from cosmic rays. The wavenumber separation (Δ) between the two main peaks (Fermi diad bands) of the CO2 Raman spectrum was determined using a spectrum data processing software (GRAMS/AI) for baseline correction and peak fitting with a mixed Gaussian/Lorentzian method. The measured Δ values were normalized by repeated measurements of an in-house standard sample (CO2 fluid inclusion in clinopyroxene; density = 1.166 g/cm3) analyzed every five unknown sample runs. The normalized Δ value was converted to the CO2 density after the method given in Yamamoto and Kagi (2006). The data with CO2 density lower than 0.1 g/cm3 were discarded because of the lack of the calibration curve. The olivine samples were kept at 40 °C on a heating stage during measurements so that CO2 in shrinkage bubbles had a single phase above the critical point. The analytical uncertainties mostly depend on the intensity of the peaks of the Fermi diad bands. The error of each sample run was estimated using a relationship between the peak intensity and error of the Δ values previously determined by repeated measurements of standards (Supplementary Fig. S1).

The volume of an individual melt inclusion and a bubble inside was measured with MXCT (Fig. 1). A doubly polished olivine grain containing melt inclusion(s) was placed on a sample stage of an MXCT system (ScanXmate D160TSS105; Comscantechno Co. Ltd.) at the Yokosuka Headquarter of Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology (JAMSTEC) (Ujiié et al., 2019). The analytical conditions were optimized to acquire a 3D quantitative densitometry of bubbles and glasses in melt inclusions and host olivine crystals. The measured length was calibrated using a standard tungsten sphere with 100 μm diameter. An isotropic voxel size of the 3D images is between 0.9 and 2.6 μm in the high-resolution settings (X-ray tube voltage of 80 kV; detector array size of 1024 × 1024, 1500 projections/360°; 1 s/projection). A 15-minute measurement was repeated three times, and the data were averaged. The 3D images were processed using Molcer Plus software (White Rabbit Corp.) The surface of the bubbles and glass in melt inclusions was smoothed using a Gaussian filter by convoluting 5 × 5 × 5 neighborhood voxels. Differences in volume calculated using filtered and unfiltered data were within 2% and 9% for the glass and bubbles, respectively. Applying different filters (e.g., bilateral filter) or various convolution sizes (e.g. 3 × 3 × 3) did not cause a significant change in the calculated volume (<10%).

After the micro-Raman spectrometry and MXCT, each olivine grain was mounted on acryl resin and polished to expose melt inclusions with a lapping film with alumina particles. After removing acryl resin with acetone, olivine grains were mounted on indium disks for SIMS (IMS 1280HR; CAMECA) at Kochi Institute for Core Sample Research of JAMSTEC (Shimizu et al., 2017). A primary Cs+ beam was defocused to a 15-μm spot on the sample surface, and secondary ions from the 5 × 5 μm area in the center of the spot were transmitted to the ion optics. The 16O1H− and 12C− signal intensities were measured along with 19F−, 32S−, 35Cl−, and 31P− using a magnetic peak switching method and normalized with 30Si− to determine H2O and CO2 concentrations (Hanyu et al., 2019; Shimizu et al., 2017). The standard deviation of H2O and CO2 measurements is <1.4% and <3.2%, respectively, estimated by repeated measurements of the basaltic glass standard EPR-G3. Analytical details are given in Shimizu et al. (2017).

Measured chemical composition was corrected by considering the effect of post-entrapment crystallization (PEC) using the major element data of melt inclusions and host olivine. The details for this correction are described elsewhere (Hanyu et al., 2019). Briefly, we assumed the Fe/Mg partition coefficient between olivine and melt to be 0.3 (Putirka et al., 2007). Olivine in equilibrium with the melt was incrementally added to or subtracted from the melt with 0.01 wt% step until the melt was in equilibrium with the host olivine in terms of Fe/Mg (Wallace et al., 2015). The correction factor for the addition/subtraction of olivine in equilibrium with melt inclusions is shown in Supplementary Table S1. The correction factor for most of the samples were less than 10%.

The total CO2 concentration in melt inclusions was calculated by summing CO2 in glass and shrinkage bubbles. The error sources in this calculation are CO2 density measurement in bubbles by Raman spectroscopy, CO2 concentration measurement in glass with SIMS, and bubble/glass volume ratio determined by MXCT. Using errors for the bubble density and glass concentration and a 10% error for the volume ratio measurement (see above), an integrated error for the total CO2 concentration of 5–14% was found (Supplementary Table S1).

3. Results

3.1. Shape and dimension of glass and shrinkage bubbles in melt inclusions

The size of the studied melt inclusions was measured from 3D images acquired by MXCT, where the voxel data of MXCT were analyzed using a 3D image-processing software. Their longest axis (amxct) ranges from 36 to 241 μm. Here, we define the middle axis (bmxct) as the second longest axis that is perpendicular to amxct and the shortest axis (cmxct) as the one perpendicular to amxct and bmxct in the 3D images. Most melt inclusions show bmxct/amxct between 0.7 and 0.95 and cmxct/amxct between 0.4 and 0.9 (Supplementary Fig. S2).

The longest axis measured under a microscope (ams) is nearly identical to amxct for most melt inclusions (Fig. 2). The axis perpendicular to ams on the microscope plane (bms) is broadly correlated with bmxct and cmxct. However, some melt inclusions show a departure from the equiline in bms–bmxct and bms–cmxct spaces.

The melt inclusion volume was directly acquired from the voxel data of MXCT (Vmxct). This volume was compared with the volume calculated using dimensions of melt inclusions measured under a microscope (i.e., ams and bms), as often applied in previous studies. Because the length of melt inclusions perpendicular to the microscope plane (cms) is hard to measure, cms is assumed to be equal to bms. Another assumption for the calculation was that melt inclusions were ellipsoidal in shape. The melt inclusion volume calculated in this way (Vms) is generally greater than Vmxct. This tendency is prominent for large melt inclusions with a volume greater than ~0.3 × 106 μm3 (Fig. 3). By contrast, the bubble volume estimated from the microscopic method is broadly consistent with that determined using MXCT.

Melt inclusions in olivine from Rairua and Anatonu basalts show different ranges in the melt inclusion volume and bubble volume%, as shown in Fig. 4. The melt inclusions in Anatonu basalts had a wide range in the melt inclusion volume (up to ~1.6 × 106 μm3) with a relatively low bubble volume% (<6.5% except for one sample). The melt inclusions in Rairua basalts have a small melt inclusion volume (<0.37 × 106 μm3 except for one sample) with a high bubble volume% (up to 21%) relative to those in Anatonu basalts.

3.2. CO2 and H2O in glass and bubbles in melt inclusions

The density of CO2 in shrinkage bubbles is up to 0.39 g/cm3. The bubble CO2 density is not correlated with the bubble volume, melt inclusion volume, or bubble volume% (Supplementary Fig. S3).

CO2 and H2O concentrations in glass were determined by SIMS after polishing out the melt inclusions. The H2O concentration ranges from nearly zero to 1.2 wt% and is not correlated with the heating temperature, lithophile elements (e.g., Ce), or other volatile elements. Possible water loss from melt inclusions has been suggested during rehomogenization due to high hydrogen diffusivity in the olivine matrix (Bucholz et al., 2013; Chen et al., 2011; Gaetani et al., 2012; Kent, 2008). Although the peak temperature for melting was kept as low as possible (typically 1180–1280 °C) and the heating time at this temperature was short (5 min) during heating experiments, water loss from melt inclusions may have not been fully avoided. However, the variation in H2O concentration exhibits no correlation with the size of melt inclusions (Supplementary Fig. S4). Moreover, melt inclusions in the same host basalts show a small range in the H2O concentration (within 0.3 wt% interval except for melt inclusions in RAV-27 and RAV-33; Supplementary Fig. S4), which is hardly caused by water diffusion during the heating experiments. The overall variation in the H2O concentration observed in the studied samples can be ascribed to H2O degassing from magmas before or during eruption rather than diffusive H2O loss from melt inclusions during rehomogenization. Water in shrinkage bubbles is difficult to detect. Many previous studies have not counted H2O in bubbles to estimate total H2O in melt inclusions because of high solubility of H2O in the melt (e.g., Dixon, 1997; Moore et al., 2015; Wallace et al., 2015). Shaw et al. (2008) estimated that bubbles may contain up to 2% of total H2O in melt inclusions in Mariana arc basalts. However, a precaution arises for melt inclusions with low H2O abundance from the study of those in Mt. Somma-Vesuvius basalts; Esposito et al. (2016) reported the presence of H2O in shrinkage bubbles, which adds up to 500 ppm H2O to the total abundance in the melt inclusions.

CO2 is unlikely to be diffused out from melt inclusions after their entrapment in olivine (Yamamoto et al., 2011). However, CO2 exsolution in magmas before the melt inclusion entrapment is a likely process during magma degassing (Boudoire et al., 2018; Hartley et al., 2014; Kent, 2008). To discriminate the data potentially affected by degassing, the data with glass CO2 concentration lower and higher than 200 ppm are shown by different symbols in the figures. While glass CO2 concentration in Anatonu melt inclusions was relatively low (<1200 ppm), Rairua melt inclusions showed a higher glass CO2 concentration as a group (up to 7600 ppm) (Fig. 5; Supplementary Table S1).

For most melt inclusions, the amount of CO2 in bubbles exceeds that in glass (Fig. 5). The total CO2 concentration in melt inclusions is calculated as that bubbles were dissolved in glass using the volume ratio of glass and bubbles determined by MXCT, assuming a density of 2.8 g/cm3 for glass (Stolper and Walker, 1980). The maximum total CO2 concentration in Anatonu melt inclusions was 6300 ppm, which corresponds to approximately 5 kb saturation pressure in the H2O–CO2 system using the VolatileCalc model (Newman and Lowenstern, 2002) at 1280 °C with SiO2 = 46 wt%. Some Rairua melt inclusions had even greater total CO2 concentration.

4. Discussion

4.1. Shape and volume of melt inclusions

The size of melt inclusions determined from the MXCT images is compared with that measured under a microscope (Fig. 2). Most samples are plotted close to the equiline in ams–amxct space, because olivine was purposely mounted in acryl resin so that the longest axis of melt inclusions was subparallel to the doubly polished surfaces. Some melt inclusions with the longest axis being oblique to the microscope plane have ams smaller than amxct. On the other hand, the data show some scatter in bms–bmxct and bms–cmxct spaces, where most melt inclusions have cmxct ≤ bms ≤ bmxct. This is best explained by the random orientation of the b and c axes of melt inclusions. The values of bms measured under a microscope are dependent on how melt inclusions are placed relative to the microscope plane.

The problem with using a microscope is that the thickness of melt inclusions perpendicular to the microscope plane (cms) is difficult to measure (Tucker et al., 2019). In previous studies, the melt inclusion volume was estimated with the assumption that cms equals to bms and that melt inclusions have an ellipsoidal shape (Hartley et al., 2014; Neave et al., 2014; Shaw et al., 2008; Wallace et al., 2015; Wanless et al., 2015). A discordance between Vms and Vmxct (Fig. 3) is partially caused by a disputable assumption of cms = bms, but the shape of melt inclusions is worth being evaluated here. From a visual inspection, the larger melt inclusions tend to have a more angular shape. The shape characteristic is represented by the ratio of Vmxct against Vellips, which corresponds to the calculated volume using the dimensions of melt inclusions determined from MXCT images (i.e., amxct, bmxct, and cmxct) and assuming ellipsoidal shape (i.e., Vellips = 4π/3 × (amxct/2)(bmxct/2)(cmxct/2)) (Fig. 6). Small melt inclusions (amxct < 80 μm) show Vmxct/Vellips > 0.8, indicating that their shape resembles ellipsoids. By contrast, large melt inclusions tend to have a lower Vmxct/Vellips down to the value of cone (0.5) or octahedron (1/π ~0.32).

Whether a melt inclusion has ellipsoidal or angular shape may not be always evaluated by projection on a plane. The shape characteristic of cross section of melt inclusion is quantified by Smxct/Selllips (Fig. 6). Smxct is the cross sectional area of melt inclusions on the horizontal plane, as if they were placed and observed under microscope, determined using voxel data of MXCT. Selllips is the cross sectional area calculated using aSmxct and bSmxct assuming ellipsoidal shape (i.e., Sellips = π × (aSmxct/2)(bSmxct/2)), where aSmxct and bSmxct are the longer and shorter axes on the same horizontal plane. Melt inclusions with low Smxct/Selllips tend to show low Vmxct/Vellips, indicating that they have angular shape rather than ellipsoidal shape. However, a group of melt inclusions have low Vmxct/Vellips despite of Smxct/Selllips being close to unity. These melt inclusions should have angular shape in 3D, although they apparently display an ellipsoidal cross section on the horizontal plane. For example, RAV-33_OL-14_MI-01 exhibits ellipsoidal cross section from a certain view point (Smxct/Selllips = 1.06), whereas it looks more like rhombic shape from another view point (Smxct/Selllips = 0.84) (Fig. 6).

The shape of large melt inclusions may be influenced by the crystal form of the host olivine (i.e., negative crystal). The observation of the natural and experimental melt inclusions suggests that initially rounded melt inclusions reequilibrate to a negative crystal shape by dissolving and precipitating host minerals (Frezzotti, 2001; Schiano et al., 2006). In this case, the ellipsoidal shape assumption gives rise to the overestimation of the melt inclusion volume by the microscopic method.

The bubble volume estimated from the microscopic method is broadly consistent with that determined by the MXCT images (Fig. 3). Because most bubbles are nearly spherical in shape, the diameter of bubbles measured under a microscope gives a reasonable estimate of the volume of bubble spheres. The small difference in volume determined by the two methods (up to ~20%) is unclear. Notably, it may be difficult to optically determine the boundary of bubbles because of refraction at the bubble edges.

4.2. Formation of shrinkage bubbles

The bubble volume% of the studied melt inclusions range from 1.2% to 20.7%. The formation of shrinkage bubbles is caused by the combined effects of PEC, the thermal contraction of melt and host olivine, and melt density change caused by water loss from melt inclusions (Aster et al., 2016; Bucholz et al., 2013; Danyushevsky et al., 2002; Gaetani et al., 2012; Kent, 2008; Moore et al., 2015; Schiavi et al., 2016; Steele-MacInnis et al., 2011; Wallace et al., 2015). PEC is a mechanism that first generates shrinkage bubbles in melt inclusions. Because olivine has a smaller specific volume than melt, olivine crystallization from basaltic melt on the wall of melt inclusions results in a smaller volume of residual melt than the cavity surrounded by host olivine. The formation of shrinkage bubbles caused by PEC in slowly cooling magma is dependent on the temperature difference at the time of melt entrapment and that of the final ascent of the carrier magma before eruption. Assuming 100 °C intervals between them, the difference in bubble volume% in melt inclusions is estimated to be 1–2% for basaltic melt inclusions in olivine (Maclennan, 2017; Moore et al., 2015).

The thermal contraction of the melt is a predominant mechanism for forming and expanding shrinkage bubbles (Aster et al., 2016; Maclennan, 2017; Moore et al., 2015; Schiano and Bourdon, 1999; Tait, 1992; Zhang, 1998). The melt volume reduces in accordance with the increase in melt density during cooling from the eruption temperature to the glass transition temperature, the latter of which is between 600 °C and 800 °C for the basaltic melt (Dingwell and Webb, 1990; Gottsmann et al., 2004). Although the volume change in host olivine moderates this effect, the contraction rate for melt exceeds that for olivine (e.g., Tait, 1992; Zhang, 1998; Danyushevsky et al., 2002; Kent, 2008). According to a model proposed by Moore et al. (2015), melt and olivine contraction is approximately 6% and 2%, respectively, at 800 °C and 10% and 3%, respectively, at 600 °C due to the cooling from the starting temperature of 1200 °C. Consequently, shrinkage bubbles would likely expand for 4–7% in volume during cooling/quenching after magma eruption and rehomogenization experiments.

The extent of melt contraction during cooling is also a function of H2O concentration in the melt. A hydrous rhyolitic melt contracts to a greater extent than an anhydrous melt along a given cooling path (Moore et al., 2015). By contrast, the rate of contraction is almost similar between hydrous and anhydrous basaltic melts unless H2O is lost from the hydrous melt during cooling. The dehydration of melt inclusions enhances melt contraction because the density of the hydrous melt is smaller than that of the anhydrous melt (Aster et al., 2016; Mysen, 1977; Ochs and Lange, 1999; Schiavi et al., 2016). Previous heating experiments showed that hydrogen diffuses through olivine grains with the distance of a few millimeters in a time scale of tens of minutes near the melting temperature of basalts (Chen et al., 2011; Bucholz et al., 2013; Gaetani et al., 2012; Kent, 2008). In our reheating experiments, water loss from melt inclusions should have been minimized by keeping the samples at the melting temperature for a short time interval (5 min). This is supported by the fact that melt inclusions from the same basalts show a limited range in H2O concentration, suggesting that diffusive H2O loss during heating experiments is not a major cause of the overall variation in H2O (Supplementary Fig. S4). Because H2O is not correlated with any other elements, partial melting or fractional crystallization of magmas would not be a mechanism responsible for modifying the H2O concentration in the studied samples. We suggest that the large variation in the H2O concentration from nearly zero up to 1.2 wt% is a consequence of water degassing of host basalts either in a magma chamber or during lava emplacement. Because of the high diffusivity of hydrogen, melt inclusions are probably in equilibrium with the host magma through the olivine matrix in terms of H2O (Bucholz et al., 2013; Chen et al., 2011; Gaetani et al., 2012). If the host magma is degassed before or during an eruption, then the melt inclusions may lose water accordingly. Lack of correlation between H2O concentration and the melt inclusion size implies that water loss was a slow process compared to the time scale of hydrogen diffusion in olivine matrix (tens of minutes for a few millimeters as discussed above) (Supplementary Fig. S4). This contracts to a group of olivine-hosted melt inclusions from Mangaia which show a positive correlation between H2O concentration and melt inclusion size, while the other group of melt inclusions show relatively high H2O concentration irrespective of their size (Cabral et al., 2014). Host basalts could have experienced different cooling path that might be recorded in H2O concentration in melt inclusions. Assuming an initial H2O concentration of 1.2 wt% at the time of melt encapsulation, full dehydration induces the contraction of basaltic melt for approximately 3 vol% at 1200 °C, using a thermochemical model of a hydrous melt (Ueki and Iwamori, 2016; see also Ghiorso and Sack, 1995; Ghiorso et al., 2002).

In sum, if the formation of shrinkage bubbles is due solely to PEC, then the bubble volume% is expected to be less than 2%. Initially, hydrated melt inclusions (1.2 wt% H2O) would have an additional bubble volume% for up to 3% after dehydration, as shown above. Consequently, bubble volume% should be less than 5% in olivine-hosted melt inclusions before the eruption (and at the melting temperature during the heating experiments). Melt contraction by cooling to the glass transition temperature induces bubble expansion for 4–7 vol%, as discussed above. Considering these estimates, bubble volume% greater than 12% observed in three samples is apparently too large (Fig. 4, Fig. 5, Supplementary Fig. S3). A group of melt inclusions with extensively high bubble volume% has been interpreted as the simultaneous entrapment of melt and CO2 fluid during host olivine crystallization (Frezzotti, 2001; Moore et al., 2015). Primary fluid inclusions are occasionally found in olivine phenocrysts, suggesting that the magma was saturated with CO2 when olivine crystallized.

4.3. CO2 in glass and shrinkage bubbles

The amount of CO2 in bubbles is generally greater than that in glass in the studied samples (Fig. 5). The total CO2 is broadly correlated with the CO2 density in bubbles and more tightly with bubble volume%, indicating that shrinkage bubbles are a major host for CO2 in melt inclusions after rehomogenization (Fig. 5). Here, we discuss the distribution of CO2 between glass and bubbles during quenching in the heating stage.

The presence of bubbles was recognized for all samples during heating experiments. In the following discussion, we assume that CO2 was in equilibrium between the melt phase (glass after quenching) and fluid phase (bubbles) at the melting temperature during heating experiments (assumed at a fixed temperature of 1200 °C for simplicity). When quenching, the rapid cooling prevents the exchange of CO2 between the phases. The density of CO2 fluids was decreased according to the increase of bubble volume caused by the contraction of the melt phase during cooling from the melting temperature to the glass transition temperature. In this model, the measured CO2 in the glass is controlled by the solubility at the melting temperature just before quenching.

We apply the CO2 solubility model given in Shishkina et al. (2014) to calculate CO2 distribution between glass and bubbles at 1200 °C. While CO2 solubility is less sensitive to the presence of H2O when the H2O concentration is low (e.g., <2 wt%), it is strongly controlled by melt composition (Brooker et al., 2001; Dixon, 1997; Mysen et al., 1975). In general, CO2 solubility increases as alkali elements increase and SiO2 decreases. The compositional effect on CO2 solubility is parameterized with Π*, where Π* = (Ca2+ + 0.8 K+ + 0.7Na+ + 0.4Mg2+ + 0.4Fe2+)/(Si4+ + Al3+) (Shishkina et al., 2014). The Rairua melt inclusions have higher Π* than the Anatonu melt inclusions as a group because the former has lower SiO2 and higher alkali contents than the latter. The majority of Rairua and Anatonu melt inclusions plot on and slightly above the isobaric line of CO2 partial pressure (PCO2) at 100 MPa (Fig. 7). This finding suggests that the variation in the CO2 concentration in the glass is mostly explained by the CO2 solubility as a function of the melt composition. However, three melt inclusions with SiO2-undersaturated composition (i.e., basanite to nephelinite) show apparently high PCO2 relative to the other samples.

Using an equation of state for CO2, PCO2 can be converted to the density of CO2 at the melting temperature. The equation of state including the effect of the departure from the ideal gas state (i.e., compressibility factor) is taken from Sterner and Pitzer (1994). Fig. 8 shows the calculated CO2 density from PCO2 data at 1200 °C compared with the measured CO2 density in bubbles (i.e., at 40 °C). The majority of samples plot above the equiline, indicating that bubbles expanded during quenching. However, some samples, particularly those with low CO2 in glass (< 200 ppm) plot close to or below the equiline. It is unlikely that the bubble volume is reduced during cooling. A possible explanation may be the excessive CO2 transfer from melt to bubbles. If cooling is sufficiently slow relative to the time scale of CO2 exchange between melt and fluid phases, then CO2 in the melt should be controlled by the solubility at temperatures lower than the melting temperature. However, the fact that CO2 solubility is less dependent on the temperature does not support this theory (Pan et al., 1991). An apparent CO2 depletion in glass might be explained by the exsolution of CO2 from the melt in forming carbon-bearing phases. The presence of tiny carbonates and a thin film of CO2-bearing phases, which is usually invisible under a microscope, has been reported to occur at the interface between the glass and bubbles and between the glass and host mineral (Esposito et al., 2014; Helo et al., 2011; Kamenetsky et al., 2001; Kamenetsky et al., 2007; Moore et al., 2015; Steele-MacInnis et al., 2017). Because carbonates inside the bubble wall are likely to precipitate from vapor phase rather than melt phase, the formation of such carbonates would not be the major cause of low CO2 concentration in melt (glass). Moreover, carbonates at the bubble-glass boundary could be dissolved in melt during reheating experiments (Wallace et al., 2015). Alternatively, some CO2 can be sequestered from melt into minerals crystallized in a CO2-enriched zone formed by continuous crystallization near the glass-host mineral interface or into carbonates or CO2-rich gas phase trapped in cracks along the interface (Esposito et al., 2014; Moore et al., 2015; Steele-MacInnis et al., 2011). If reheating time was insufficient to dissolve such invisible CO2-rich minerals or phases at the glass-host mineral interface, CO2 concentration in glass might be apparently lower than the original concentration (Moore et al., 2015).

Assuming no CO2 exchange between melt and bubbles during quench after the heating experiments, the bubble expansion rate during cooling is computed by the calculated CO2 density (i.e., the inverse of molar volume) at the melting temperature divided by the measured CO2 density below the glass transition temperature (i.e., at 40 °C). Using this value and measured bubble volume% with MXCT, bubble volume% at the melting temperature can be calculated (Fig. 9). The extent of bubble expansion during cooling (δVcooling) is estimated by subtracting the calculated initial bubble volume% from the measured bubble volume% (below the glass transition temperature). These values are compared with the theoretical values of the melt contraction during cooling discussed in the previous section. Except for melt inclusions with low CO2 concentration in glass (< 200 ppm), all samples but two showed δVcooling within the value expected during cooling (7% at maximum assuming the glass transition temperature at 600 °C). If we assume the glass transition temperature at 800 °C, then additional two samples have δVcooling higher than the expected value (4%). Anomalously high δVcooling is associated with the large measured bubble volume% (>9%) and high total CO2 (>10,000 ppm). Although the reason for such a high δVcooling is unclear, excess δVcooling may be ascribed to the oversaturation of CO2 in the melt under the condition of very high PCO2 in fluid phases because the oversaturation of CO2 in melt gives rise to apparently higher calculated CO2 density in the bubble and hence higher δVcooling.

The samples with δVcooling < 4% (except for melt inclusions with glass CO2 concentration lower than 200 ppm) show calculated initial bubble volume% up to 5.4%. Considering the uncertainties for this estimate, these values are within the theoretical limit expected by the effect of PEC (up to 2 vol%) and dehydration (up to 3 vol%), as discussed above. The effect of dehydration on expanding shrinkage bubbles is presented in Fig. 10. The melt inclusions with high H2O (> 0.7 wt%) have calculated bubble volume% lower than ~2% except for one sample (RAV-33_OL-03_MI-01). By contrast, the melt inclusions with low H2O (< 0.3 wt%) have a variably high bubble volume% (>2%). This finding suggests that water loss from melt inclusions, probably in magma before or during an eruption, is partly responsible for the enhancing melt contraction and bubble expansion.

4.4. CO2 in Raivavae basalts

The basalts from Rairua and Anatonu Formations are clearly distinguished by their elemental and isotopic composition (Hanyu et al., 2019; Lassiter et al., 2003; Lassiter et al., 2002; Maury et al., 2013; Miyazaki et al., 2018). The Rairua basalts have more radiogenic Pb isotopes (e.g., lower 207Pb/206Pb) than the Anatonu basalts. Similarly, olivine-hosted melt inclusions in the Rairua basalts generally show lower 207Pb/206Pb than those in the Anatonu basalts with some exceptions (Hanyu et al., 2019). A small number of melt inclusions in the Anatonu basalts have low 207Pb/206Pb within the range defined by Rairua basalts, and vice versa. This suggests the presence of two basalt sources, HIMU source with low 207Pb/206Pb and depleted mantle source with high 207Pb/206Pb, and melts from these sources are partially intermingled in magmas from the depleted (high 207Pb/206Pb) and HIMU (low 207Pb/206Pb) mantle sources.

Glass CO2 concentration is higher in Rairua melt inclusions than that in Anatonu melt inclusions as a group (Fig. 5, Fig. 7). The difference in the glass CO2 concentration does not always reflect the difference in the CO2 concentration in magmas when melt inclusions were entrapped because glass CO2 concentration may be controlled by the composition-dependent solubility (Shishkina et al., 2014). The total CO2 concentration in melt inclusions should be considered to compare the pre-eruption CO2 concentration in the two types of basalts.

Discriminating three Rairua melt inclusions with a large bubble volume% (>12%), the range of total CO2 concentration overlaps between the Rairua and Anatonu melt inclusions. Although all Anatonu melt inclusions have a glass CO2 concentration lower than 1000 ppm, the total CO2 amounts up to ~6300 ppm. The Rairua melt inclusions show total CO2 concentration up to ~7200 ppm except for one sample with ~15,000 ppm CO2 (RAV-32_OL-05_MI-01). Because this sample has the highest Nb concentration (~150 ppm) among the studied melt inclusions (Hanyu et al., 2019; Hanyu et al., in preparation), a very high CO2 may be a consequence of a low-degree partial melting of the magma source (Fig. 11). The ratio of CO2/Nb is often used to describe CO2 enrichment relative to lithophile elements with a similar incompatibility. Both Rairua and Anatonu melt inclusions show CO2/Nb up to 200. This value is higher than CO2/Nb previously reported in melt inclusions from HIMU basalts from Mangaia (up to 50) (Cabral et al., 2014). Because magmas were likely saturated with CO2 before the entrapment of melt inclusions, this value provides the minimum estimate of CO2/Nb in the magma source of HIMU basalts. However, we cannot assert if the HIMU source has a high CO2/Nb relative to the MORB source, the typical value of which is ~300 (Shimizu et al., 2016).

The three melt inclusions with a bubble volume% greater than the theoretical limit (12%) have a high total CO2 (>10,000 ppm). The excess bubble volume% and high total CO2 would be caused by a simultaneous entrapment of the melt and CO2 fluid as a single inclusion during olivine crystallization (Fig. 5). Consequently, these samples do not provide any information on CO2 in magmas. Notably, these inclusions have a high incompatible element concentration (e.g., Nb) compared with the other inclusions. Because Nb does not exhibit a correlation with MgO, crystal fractionation is unlikely the cause of the elevated incompatible element concentration. Instead, a low-degree partial melting would be responsible for the enrichment of incompatible lithophile elements together with CO2 in magmas. We suggest that such magmas are easily saturated with CO2 at depth, resulting in forming CO2-rich fluids in them. There are more chances for encapsulating melt and fluid simultaneously during the olivine crystallization in magmas generated by a low-degree of partial melting.

5. Concluding remarks

A precise determination of volatile contents in magmas is of paramount importance in many fields, such as mantle geochemistry and volcanology. Volatiles play a significant role in driving magma ascent to eruption via volatile exsolution and segregation from melts. Melt inclusions provide valuable information about the pre-eruption volatile composition in magmas. However, it is challenging to determine CO2 in melt inclusions due to the presence of CO2 in the melt and shrinkage bubbles. CO2 concentration in glass (formed from the melt) can be precisely determined by SIMS and FT-IR. Micro-Raman spectroscopy offers a robust approach to measure CO2 density in fluids (bubbles) and has been frequently employed in the study of fluid inclusions in mantle xenoliths. This method can also be applied to shrinkage bubbles in melt inclusions if they are filled with high-density CO2 fluids (>0.1 g/cm3). The last step is to measure the bubble-to-glass volume ratio to find out the total CO2 in melt inclusions.

The dimensions of melt inclusions and bubbles have been measured using microscopic techniques in previous studies. However, the volume of melt inclusions has not been precisely measured due to the difficulty in determining the dimension perpendicular to the microscope plane. Moreover, the assumption of ellipsoidal shape is not always guaranteed. Melt inclusions tend to have more angular shapes as their size increases in Raivavae melt inclusions. The 3D analysis of melt inclusions and bubbles by MXCT provides a quantitative determination of the volumes of melt inclusions and bubbles and, therefore, their volume ratios. The combination of micro-Raman spectrometry, MXCT, and SIMS analyses on melt inclusions can be applied to reliably estimate CO2 concentration in pre-eruptive magmas.

  • High-C content and CO<inf>2</inf>/Ba ratio of the Earth's enriched upper mantle

    2023, Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta

    One of the fundamental constraints on the carbon content in the Earth’s mantle comes from depleted mid-ocean ridge basalts (D-MORB) that experienced minimal CO degassing. The CO/Ba ratio of 120 ± 20 in these D-MORB have been used to estimate the CO content in more enriched MORB (e.g., N- and E-MORB) that have lost CO through degassing. However, it has been unclear as to how constant the CO/Ba ratio is in D-, N-, and E-MORB, which are known to derive from partial melting of a chemically and isotopically heterogeneous upper mantle. In this study, we constrained the CO/Ba ratio of the E-MORB mantle source in the Pacific by studying the compositions of MORB glass samples from the southern East Pacific Rise (on– and off-axial SEPR and Garrett transform fault) as well as volcanic glass samples from the Pukapuka ridges and Rano Rahi seamounts that extend to the west of the SEPR. Some of the submarine glasses from the Rano Rahi seamounts are D-MORB with highly depleted CO and incompatible trace element contents, but with isotopic composition pointing to a long-term enriched mantle source. These lavas were generated by re-melting of the residual Pacific E-MORB mantle source that had undergone a recent melting episode responsible for the Pukapuka ridge magmatism. Some Rano Rahi seamount lavas experienced limited CO degassing during eruption, and we consider that their most reliable pre-degassing CO/Ba ratio is the maximum value of 241 ± 30, measured in the most trace element depleted but isotopically enriched sample. While we show that this high CO/Ba ratio is in part due to fractionation during the earlier melting event that generated the Pukapuka ridges, the estimated initial CO/Ba ratio of the Pacific E-MORB mantle source is , still higher on average than that of the D-MORB mantle source (120 ± 20). We use this CO/Ba ratio for the Pacific E-MORB mantle source to provide an estimate of its CO content of ppm. We speculate that the high CO/Ba and C-enriched nature of the Pacific E-MORB mantle source could originate from either (1) recycling of oceanic lithosphere at subduction zones or (2) foundering of metasomatized continental lithospheric mantle into the convecting mantle.
